Let’s start with the most basic question first: why does async even exist?

Picture this: you have a function that calls an LLM API. The API takes, say, 3 seconds to respond. In normal (“synchronous”) Python, your program just… freezes for those 3 seconds. It can’t do anything else — not handle another user’s request, not print anything, nothing. It’s stuck waiting.

def call_llm():
    print("Sending request...")
    response = requests.post(url, json=payload)  # program freezes here for 3 sec
    print("Got response!")
    return response


If this were a web server handling 100 users, and each call takes 3 seconds, users would have to queue up one behind another. That’s bad.

Async is a way of saying: “while you’re waiting on this slow thing, go do something useful instead, and come back to this later.”

